<HEADLINE>
DOH CONFIRMS FIRST INDIGENOUS CASE OF PARATYPHOID FEVER THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 23 (CNA) 03/23/07  18:03:16 (By Lilian Wu)
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health (DOH) confirmed Friday the first
indigenous case of paratyphoid fever this year.
</P>
<P>
DOH officials said the 53-year-old man from Taipei's Tatung
District began to develop symptoms including high fever and
liquid feces March 18 and was confirmed to have been infected
with the contagious disease Friday.
</P>
<P>
The patient is now undergoing  antibiotic  treatment in a
quarantine ward, they said.
</P>
<P>
Tseng Shu-huei, a deputy section chief of DOH's Center for
Disease Control, said Taiwan confirmed 76 cases of paratyphoid
fever, a disease caused by a gram- negative bacterium, over the
past five years, of which 44 were imported and 32 indigenous.
</P>
<P>
Paratyphoid fever is marked by high fever, headache, loss of
appetite, vomiting, and constipation or diarrhea. The patient
typically develops an enlarged spleen.
</P>
<P>
Outbreaks often come in the summer; the disease can be spread
through food or water contaminated by the feces or urine of the
patients or others carrying the bacterium.
</P>
<P>
In terms of indigenous cases, health officials said that Taipei
County had the most cases with eight, followed by Hsinchu City,
Changhua County and Kaohsiung City (three cases each) , Taipei
City, Taichung County, Tainan County and Kaohsiung County (two
cases each), and one case each for Tainan and Chiayi cities and
Taoyuan, Hsinchu, Yilan, Pingtung, and Penghu counties.
</P>
